<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-116-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 116 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  April 1989 v9 n4 p33(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DARPA to fund high-density TV. (Newsletter Digest: AdvancedMilitary Computing)(Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) iscalling for contract proposals for development of low-cost,high-definition television displays.andP;  The displays will be used inweapons to show text, characters and video signals.andP;  They may alsobe used in tanks, airplanes, helicopters and simulators.andP;  DARPAhopes to combat Japanese and European competition in HDTVdevelopment.andP;  The HDTV market is expected to create new demand forDRAM chips and DARPA has long been concerned about lack of USsuppliers of these and other critical computer components.andP;  TheHDTV market could involve tens of billions of dollars intelevision and broadcasting equipment as well as dominance in theworld semiconductor market.andP;  The Japanese have reportedly invested$700 million in HDTV research and plan to bring products to marketin 1990.andP;  European firms reportedly have invested $200 million.andO;DARPA will not say how much it is investing in HDTV.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Zenith Electronics Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    ZE.andO;Topic:     United States. Defense Advanced Research Projects AgencyGovernment FundingResearch and DevelopmentHigh definition televisionCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>